  "prompt": "What is the difference between Realism and Pragmatism?",
  "response": "Realism and Pragmatism are two philosophical approaches with distinct characteristics:\n\nRealism:\n1. Focuses on objective reality existing independently of human perception\n2. Emphasizes that truth and knowledge exist objectively, regardless of individual beliefs\n3. Believes in universal principles and absolute truths\n4. Tends to be more theoretical and abstract\n5. Seeks to understand the world as it fundamentally is\n6. Prominent in metaphysics and epistemology\n7. Advocates for understanding objective facts and natural laws\n\nPragmatism:\n1. Emphasizes practical consequences and real-world outcomes\n2. Judges the value of ideas by their practical utility and effectiveness\n3. Believes truth is relative and context-dependent\n4. More action-oriented and flexible\n5. Focuses on solving problems and achieving workable solutions\n6. Values experimentation and empirical evidence\n7. Prioritizes what works over abstract philosophical considerations\n\nKey Differences:\n- Realism is more concerned with absolute truth, while Pragmatism focuses on practical effectiveness\n- Realism seeks objective understanding, Pragmatism seeks functional solutions\n- Realism is more philosophical and theoretical, Pragmatism is more practical and adaptable\n\nBoth approaches offer valuable perspectives for understanding knowledge and reality, but with different fundamental orientations.",
